    "title": "Risk of Seizure Recurrence Due to Autoimmune Encephalitis With NMDAR, LGI1, CASPR2, and GABABR Antibodies",
    "doi": "10.1212/NXI.0000000000200225",
    "authors": "Rada A, Hagemann A, Aaberg Poulsen C, et al.",
    "journal": "Neurology Neuroimmunology &amp; Neuroinflammation",
    "year": 2024,
    "outcome": "Risk of Seizure Recurrence Due to Autoimmune Encephalitis With NMDAR, LGI1, CASPR2, and GABA B R Antibodies",
    "clinical_utility": "Patients with ongoing seizures are usually not allowed to drive. The prognosis for seizure freedom is favorable in patients with autoimmune encephalitis (AIE) with antibodies against NMDA receptor (NMDAR), leucine-rich glioma-inactivated 1 (LGI1), contactin-associated protein-like 2 (CASPR2), and the gamma-aminobutyric-acid B receptor (GABA B R). We hypothesized that after a seizure-free period of 3 months, patients with AIE have a seizure recurrence risk of <20% during the subsequent 12 months.",
    "pmid": "38838283"
  },
